{
  "text": "values of the total error estimates for these two cases are equal to 0.128 and 0.013, respectively. In the case of the piezoelectricity, the estimated local and global error values are higher than in the previous two cases. The mechanical and electric parts of the average total error estimate are Finite Element Method -Simulation, Numerical Analysis and Solution Techniques 182 larger than 1, and this result is consistent with the upper bound property of the estimation present in the pure problems (compare [CITATION_1] ). In the case of the coupled piezoelectric problem, global effectivities are much greater than 1, that is, the estimated global error values are much overestimated. This suggests that some additional techniques should be applied in the error estimation by the equilibrated residual method if one wants the effectivities to become closer to 1. A remedy can be the application of the higher order equilibration [CITATION_2] in the piezoelectricity problems, instead of the linear equilibration used in this work and usually applied to pure problems.",
